# Runtime arguments for vllm-mlx serve on macOS (Apple Silicon / MLX).
#
# install.sh reads VLLM_MLX_MODEL and VLLM_MLX_ARGS, expands each into the
# LaunchAgent plist's ProgramArguments (launchd does NOT word-split env vars the
# way systemd's ExecStart does), and installs the result. To change flags later:
# edit this file (or the copy install.sh made), then re-run ./install.sh — it
# rewrites the plist and reloads the agent.
#
# The model is an MLX checkpoint resolved by name from the Hugging Face cache;
# vllm-mlx downloads it on first launch if absent. Use an MLX-native quant from
# mlx-community. On Apple Silicon the fastest 4-bit format is mxfp4 (see
# ../llama.cpp/EVALUATIONS-macos.md); nvfp4 exists for parity with the CUDA
# NVFP4 default but is ~7% slower here.
VLLM_MLX_MODEL="mlx-community/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-mxfp4"

# host 127.0.0.1 keeps the API local-only. 0.0.0.0 exposes it on the LAN; the
# server has NO auth unless --api-key is set, so firewall the port and only do
# this on a trusted network.
#
# Port 8000 matches the vLLM and ds4 deployments in this repo. ds4-macos also
# defaults to 8000; the two can still co-exist if they bind different addresses
# (ds4 on the LAN IP, this on 127.0.0.1), but they share the memory pool — run
# one at a time, or change --port here to avoid confusion.
#
# --reasoning-parser qwen3 enables per-request thinking control: clients pass
# chat_template_kwargs={"enable_thinking": false} to skip the reasoning preamble
# (bare mlx-lm cannot). Drop it for non-Qwen3 models.
VLLM_MLX_ARGS="--host 127.0.0.1 --port 8000 --reasoning-parser qwen3"

# Optional MTP speculative decoding (matches the GB10 serve flags), if the
# checkpoint ships MTP tensors:
#   --enable-mtp --mtp-num-draft-tokens 2
#
# Other useful knobs: --kv-cache-quantization [--kv-cache-quantization-bits 8],
# --enable-prefix-cache, --continuous-batching, --api-key <token>.
